This LED light bulbs normally runs for 20000 hours, if you need more spare bulbs, please search B00R25V92Y for replacement bulbs 3. If one LED Edison bulb goes out, will the rest stay lit? These light strands are connected in parallel, so one bulb broke or burnt won’t affect the rest bulb. 4. Are the porch string lights waterproof? Yes, UL listed LED outdoor string lights are IP44 waterproof. You can use the deck lights under normal weather conditions. 5. These indoor string lights be used on a dimmer? LED Outdoor string lights are dimmer compatible, it can be used on a dimmer (dimmer not included in package).

Plus, the fact that they're connectable means I can easily add more in the future if I decide to extend my little outdoor haven.One of the best parts? The ambiance they create during the evenings. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on June 23, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Great Price and Look, Mixed Durability
reviews.reviewText: I've purchased four sets of these lights in the past and am writing this review as I purchase a 5th. For the price the look is great and brings some atmosphere to whichever space you use them in (I have some in my office, living room, back patio and front patio). For an occasional-use outside feature, it'll last a long time.However, if you aim to enjoy these lights on the daily then you should be prepared to continually replace the bulbs. We have one of these sets strung across our living room and turned on each night for 5-6 Hours - our heaviest use of this product. After about a month-ish of that usage so you'll have the first bulb go out and then see one or two burn out each month afterwards. For the look and price I've been happy to replace as they burn out, but it does eventually give you the feeling of "I JUST replaced all the dead ones, now another is gone."Also, sometimes these bulbs burn extra bright when you switch them out - and if it does you should expect that particular bulb to burn out real quick. I also have seen some that appear "burnt out" which come back to life if you lightly tap on the bulb. Unfortunately, the reverse is true as well where I've bumped a working bulb while replacing one next to it and had it die on me. Ultimately the bulbs for these are finicky and not the longest lasting - but at least they're relatively cheap. If I could get the exact same look with LED bulbs instead I certainly would invest, but alas.As for durability over the longer term, the actual cord for the set of lights I put in my living room lasted about two years of heavy daily usage before last night it finally kicked the bucket. It's the only one of the 4 sets of these that has had the cord die.Ultimately great value for what you get, just anticipate some upkeep costs to keep the bright lights a-flowing.
